{"questionId":"9083243","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">A molecule of citric acid, C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>7</sub>, is shown.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/ed4fd9807f2968831cf9c0c4b39bfc4c91f9569b.png\" width=\"215\" height=\"123\"></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">The equation for the first dissociation of citric acid in water is</span></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>7</sub> (aq) + H<sub>2</sub>O (l) <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" \\rightleftharpoons \">\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">⇌</mo>\n</math></span> C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>7</sub>O<sub>7</sub><sup>−</sup> (aq) + H<sub>3</sub>O<sup>+</sup> (aq)</span></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Identify a conjugate acid–base pair in the equation.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>7</sub> <em><strong>AND</strong> </em>C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>7</sub>O<sub>7</sub><sup>−</sup><br><em><strong>OR</strong></em><br>H<sub>2</sub>O <em><strong>AND</strong> </em>H<sub>3</sub>O<sup>+</sup> ✔</span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9083243","referenceCode":"19N.2.SL.TZ0.4a(i)","subjectId":"58-dp-chemistry-first-assessment-2025","title":"Identify a conjugate acid–base pair in the equation.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a(i)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Reactivity 3. What are the mechanisms of chemical change?","Reactivity 3.1—Proton transfer reactions","Reactivity 3.1.2—A pair of species differing by a single proton is called a conjugate acid–base pair. Deduce